        <h1 class="headerWork">The Challenge</h1>
        <p>Maybe you heard what happened last night, maybe you didn't. Maybe it took you a little longer than you wanted or maybe
            you missed an important article all together. Millennials, just like most, want to be up to date with what's going on
            around them. The problem millennials face is just that, the amount of time that it often takes to read the news in it's
            entirety.</p>

        <p>"Millennial News Network" or MNN is the largest syndicate of breaking news and other news worldwide. They've asked me
            to rethink the news experience for their site (desktop). They asked us to design a compelling news site for today's generation
            of news consumers. They encouraged us to try and figure out exactly how millennials consume and share content. MNN doesn't
            want to be dogmatic about "how they've always done things." Millennial News Network wants to break new ground, they want
            this new site to take a few risks and they're counting on us to bring change to the industry. The following was the result
            of the case study.</p>
        <hr>
        <div class="processHeader">
            <img class="img-responsive progressImg" src="./images/process/empathize.png" alt="">
        </div>
        <hr>
        <h1 class="headerWork">Empathize</h1>
        <p>Empathy is defined as the ability to understand and share the feelings of another. It is an important step with the user
            experience that should not be forgotten. If we do not understand who we are designing for, it is very difficult to succeed
            with the user experience. With our tasks at hand, we had to empathize with our age group to fully understand how they
            consumed their news. We first started out with writing out a list of assumptions.</p>

        <div class="disclaimerBox">
            <div class="disclaimerTitle">Assumptions</div>
            <ul>
                <li><span>Millennials like to skim articles.</span></li>
                <li><span>Article's headlines determine if the user will read it or not.</span></li>
                <li><span>Actual news sites are rarely visited, if at all.</span></li>
                <li><span>Images and videos enhance the user experience.</span></li>
                <li><span>If the article is too long, readers will not read the article in full.</span></li>
                <li><span>People depend on social media sites for their news.</span></li>
                <li><span>People don't like the ads, and would rather not see them.</span></li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <p>After the list we set out to see if our assumptions were correct. Being a millennial myself this was an easier task as
            I know how I personally consume the news. However, I am just one millennial,and there are many more. Apart from analyzing
            ourselves, we interviewed millennials to see how they consumed their news. We wanted to also see what pain points they
            might have with getting it.</p>
            
        <p>Once we completed our interviews we came together to discuss our findings. We compiled all our interview findings into
            one document so that we could see commonalities and patterns that our millennials shared on what they needed and how
            they wanted to consume their news. We downloaded and researched some top news apps to see what they were doing right
            and read reviews on what they might be able to improve.</p>
        <hr>
        <div class="processHeader">
            <img class="img-responsive progressImg" src="./images/process/define.png" alt="">
        </div>
        <hr>
        <h1 class="headerWork">Define</h1>
        <p>Once we were able to empathize and interview many of our eventual users, we felt we had enough of an understanding to
            define exactly what we wanted to create. There were several things that stood out to us but we made a list of some 'Key Findings.' Below are the things we felt were more important in our research. It was these findings which
            would most likely lead us to the success of our website.</p>

        <div class="disclaimerBox">
            <div class="disclaimerTitle">Key Findings</div>
            <ul>
                <li><span>Millennials wanted to customize the news according to their interests.</span></li>
                <li><span>News ads were distracting and took them out of the experience.</span></li>
                <li><span>Users didn't always have a ton of time, they often wanted a quick read.</span></li>
                <li><span>Visuals enhanced the user experience.</span></li>
                <li><span>People depend on social media sites for their news.</span></li>
                <li><span>Though they wanted a quick read, they wanted to be well informed to be involved with social interactions and caught up to
                speed with everything.</span></li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <p>With our research and key findings, we created a persona. This also allowed us to keep our end user in mind throughout
            the whole process. We would often refer to our persona Cade West. We wanted to make sure we were sticking to the needs
            of our user. This was to keep us on the correct path according to what we had defined. With that in mind we knew we had
            to come up with a web application that allowed our users to save time. Time is extremely valuable to our users, as it
            is to anyone. This lead our design and was a foundation to our project. We knew if we could not save users time our app
            would be another app they would not want.</p>

        <img class="imgProp img-responsive progressImg progressImg" src="./images/mnn/mnnpersona.png" alt="">

        <hr>

