        <h1 class="headerWork">Ideate</h1>
        <p>After defining our users needs and insights, it was time to brainstorm some creative solutions for the problem. We knew
            there were several pain points we wanted to figure out how to tackle. The biggest pain point we needed to tackle was
            saving our users time. How were we going to save their time? Articles often have a ton of information. Information in
            some articles is essential and pertinent to the story itself. Some information is important but could be done away with,
            and some of the information is just a cherry on top. It might pertain to the story but the story doesn't change with
            or without it. When all the information is put together, it makes a story. A lot of our users liked to read the articles
            in their entirety, but most of the users just wanted the important information.</p>

        <p>We chose to keep the full articles for those users that wanted to read them in their entirety. Though with our users end
            goal in mind, to save time, I came up with a TL;DR (Too Long; Didn't Read) function. This ended up being our primary
            focus on the app. The TL;DR function allows readers to get the essential information of an article in just a couple sentences.
            This allowed our customers to save time, and to be well informed within seconds.</p>
        
        <p>Below is what the TL;DR button would look like with a brief description of what it is for our users.</p>

        <img class="imgProp img-responsive" src="./images/mnn/tldrbutton.png" alt="">

        <p>There were also a few other things that we did to offer time saving abilities. This did include creating an account.
            By doing so our users can customize their home feed and set preferences on what they'd like to view. It was important
            to get our users to create an account so that we could save this information for each time they logged in. On top of
            customizing their home feed, we gave an up vote and down vote option to each article. The more up votes the article receives
            the higher up on your feed it will go. This makes it so that you are reading popular and relevant news first without
            having to browse for long.</p>

        <p>Creating the account also allows our users to bookmark articles. This way if they are running low on time it will be
            saved for later. There they can easily access the articles when they have some downtime to read them. Our users can also
            set preferences as to the days and times they'd like to receive notifications. This way they aren't missing out on any
            news.</p>

        <h1 class="sectionTitle">Business vs Customer</h1>
        <p>The next task we had to take on was that of ads. Our users hated ads, but, from a business standpoint ads are important.
            They can be very lucrative and our project manager insisted that we didn't do away with ads. My group and I set out to
            find a way to include ads which also wouldn't have a negative impact with the experience for our users. We set out to
            see how different social media sites and news apps included their ads. While reviewing a few apps I was looking at my
            Instagram feed and had barely noticed that I had scrolled past a few ads. I wasn't taken out of the experience at all
            as it looked like any other picture but they were included. I felt this would be the best way to incorporate our ads
            and we added them in our article feeds.</p>

        <h1 class="sectionTitle">Where do we go from here?</h1>
        <p>Once we felt like we got some good ideas for our app, we created a user story map and determined what our minimum viable
            product would be with our project manager. We included pages we needed to get a better sense of direction. It helped
            to stay organized and helped us lay out the different components we wanted on each page. Below is the story map that
            I built to begin with.</p>

        <img class="imgProp img-responsive progressImg" src="./images/mnn/userstorymap.jpg" alt="">

        <p>After creating the story map it was time to start discovering the layout and design. We started off with our handy pens
            and paper and started to establish the structure. We started out with low fidelity grayscale mockups. This was so that
            we could test the functionality of the overall site without distracting people with the colors. Once we tested the mock-ups
            with some of or users we got some good feedback on our first iteration.</p>

        <p>There were some layout issues with spacing and how we laid out our articles. Arguably our most important feature, the
            TL;DR, wasn't viewed as an actual call to action button. It was mistaken for our logo and not something that could be
            clicked. We knew we had to make our TL;DR more visible as that was our main focus for the app and for our user. Below
            are some images of some low fidelity mock-ups that we started with and built upon those towards our final app. Of course,
            taking into consideration the feedback we received and implementing that.</p>

        <img class="imgProp img-responsive" src="./images/mnn/mnnwireframes.png" alt="">

        <h1 class="sectionTitle">Colors and Fonts</h1>
        <p>Once we tested the first couple iterations in grayscale and addressed some of the functionality issues we had we decided
            to talk about our colors. We made higher fidelity mock-ups so we could eventually get to the prototyping stage and test
            it out some more. We messed around with a lot of color palettes. We tried using some gradients, and multiple color combinations,
            but we found that by doing so it made the app feel more cluttered. Thinking back on our user, they didn't like the clutter,
            and that was something that we wanted to omit. Ultimately we chose to keep our palette really basic. We chose one color
            which would be our 'call to action' color and the rest is kept in mostly black and white, with a dark gray.</p>

        <p>Doing it this way proved to be the way to go. The black and white combination provided plenty of contrast. Readers will
            appreciate this when reading multiple articles. Overall it is a cleaner look and resembles more of a newspaper type feel.
            Afterall, we are a news website. With our website being word and content heavy we elected to choose simple texts which
            are very easy to read. As for the 'call to action' color we chose a brighter color to grab our users attention to important
            features, namely the TL;DR feature we have. In gray scale mock-ups, this feature was missed a lot so we had to make it
            pop more. We laid drop shadows behind it and made it look more like a clickable button. Through our testing we discovered
            that this helped a lot and more of our users used it.</p>

        <img class="imgProp img-responsive" src="./images/mnn/colorscheme.png" alt="">

        <h1 class="sectionTitle">Onboarding Experience</h1>

        <p>We struggled with the idea of making people sign up for our Millennial News App. From our interviews we know that some
            people can be weary of putting in information. Ultimately we decided to give them the option but we needed an account
            to meet our users needs as well. Our users wanted a way to customize their home page, comment and share articles with
            their friends. We also wanted to give them relevant news based on up votes and down votes. All these needs required us
            to have an account to save these settings. We provide an easy way to create the account through social media, or their
            email.</p>

        <p>If they choose not to sign up right away they can still browse through our app and read full articles, but, they are limited
            in their interactions. They won't be able to comment on articles, up vote/down vote articles or customize their home
            page. They are prompted to create the account if they wish to take part in those features of our app. The quick onboarding
            experience shows them these benefits and features. Our TL;DR function is also shown and they are walked through the first
            time the app is downloaded.</p>

