        <h1 class="headerWork">Test</h1>
        <p>Through testing you are able to develop your app and empathize even that much more with your users as you are able to
            see how they react with your more polished product, our testing proved very beneficial. Through testing we found a few
            issues that we were able to resolve early on in the developing process. Even before we spent countless hours making a
            high fidelity mock-up. This not only saved us a lot of time but allowed us to develop a better app according to our users
            needs. Here are just a few things we found out about through testing.</p>

        <h1 class="sectionTitle">TL;DR Feature</h1>
        <p>Our TL;DR feature or Too Long Didn't Read feature was not very visible and it was missed almost every time. The call
            to action button looked more like our logo than a button. Testing was a great time to figure this out as this was our
            "bread and butter" if you will.</p>

        <h1 class="sectionTitle">Trouble with Wording</h1>
        <p>We had a few instances where wording was confusing for our users during the testing phase. Initially we had a favorites
            feature and a bookmarked feature. To us the difference seemed obvious. Favorites were articles you liked, something you
            might want to refer to at some point down the road. Bookmarks were more of a placeholder. Something you could pull up
            later that night when you had more time to read. This wasn't the case for our users. Everyone we tested it on had the
            same question... What's the difference?</p>

        <h1 class="sectionTitle">Thumbs Up, Thumbs Down</h1>
        <p>In our early versions of the app we had a thumbs up and thumbs down feature on whether or not you liked the article.
            Through testing and feedback we quickly learned that users might be uncomfortable on what they are 'thumbs-upping'. What
            if the story was tragic or devastating? Our users felt as if they were liking something tragic. To steer away from that
            we went with an up arrow and a down arrow. To eliminate any further confusion we explained in our onboarding process
            that if you thought an article was important then you would up vote it to make it become more popular. The more up votes
            the more important it is to users the higher up on the list it is. This eliminated some uneasiness that some of our users
            experienced.</p>

        <hr>
        <img class="img-responsive progressImg" src="./images/process/conclusion.png" alt="">
        <hr>
        <h1 class="headerWork">Conclusion</h1>
        <p>So, did you hear what happened in the news last night? My hope would be is to say that you did, after all, through our
            TL;DR (Too Long; Didn't Read) feature you can get all the information you need to know within seconds. You can feel informed
            and save time. This app met two of our users biggest needs. I'm happy with the outcome so far in what we have come up
            with. It's not perfect by any means and it will continue to develop as the users' needs change. I think that is what appeals
            to me as a UX Designer, things are constantly developing. It is fun to progress with the app and to always find the best
            user experience. Overall, this was a successful case study.</p>

